    <definition xml:id="def-standard-vectors" workspace="0.5in">
      <title>The Standard Vectors</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <em>standard vectors</em> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are the vectors
          <m>\vec e_1, \vec e_2, \ldots, \vec e_n</m>.
        </p>

        <p>They are:</p>
        <me>
          \vec e_1 =
          \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0 \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec e_2 =
          \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ \vdots \\ 0 \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \ldots,
          \qquad
          \vec e_n =
          \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>

        <p>
          For example, in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec e_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec e_2=\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\\0\end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec e_3=\begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

  </page>

  <page>
    <title> Properties of Standard Vectors</title>
      <p>
        <em>Note:</em> If <m>A</m> is an <m>m\times n</m> matrix with columns
        <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2,\ldots,\vec v_n</m>, then
      </p>

      <me>
        A\vec e_i = \vec v_i, \text{ for } i=1,2,\ldots,n.
      </me>

      <p>
        So multiplying a matrix by <m>\vec e_i</m> gives column <m>i</m> of <m>A</m>.
      </p>

      <example xml:id="ex-aei-column" workspace="true">
        <title>Example</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Compute:</p>
          <me>
            \begin{bmatrix}
              1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
              4 \amp 5 \amp 6\\
              7 \amp 8 \amp 9
            \end{bmatrix}\vec e_2.
          </me>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \\ 7 \amp 8 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = 0\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix} + 1\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \\ 8 \end{bmatrix} + 0\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 6 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \\ 8 \end{bmatrix}</me> which is the second column of <m>A</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-standard-matrix">
      <title>The Standard Matrix of a Linear Transformation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> be a linear transformation.
          Then there is a unique matrix <m>A</m> such that
        </p>

        <me>
          T(\vec x)=A\vec x,
          \qquad
          \vec x\in \mathbb{R}^n.
        </me>

        <p>
          In fact, <m>A</m> is an <m>m\times n</m> matrix, and its <m>j</m>th column is
          <m>T(\vec e_j)</m>. That is,
        </p>

        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            T(\vec e_1) \amp T(\vec e_2) \amp \cdots \amp T(\vec e_n)
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The matrix <m>A</m> is the <term>standard matrix</term> for the linear transformation <m>T</m>.
    </p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-1-9-rotation-example">
    <title>Rotations</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-rotation-theta" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^2</m> defined by
          <q>rotates vectors counterclockwise by angle <m>\theta</m></q>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Let us determine <m>A</m> such that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x </m> is rotation by <m>\theta</m> degrees counterclockwise. By <xref ref="thm-standard-matrix"/>, we need to determine <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right)</m> and <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</m>.  
        </p>
        <p>
            First, note that <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right)</m> is the vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> obtained by rotating the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, which points in the direction of <m>0^\circ</m>, by <m>\theta</m> degrees counterclockwise. The resulting vector would have terminal end at the point on the unit circle whose angle is <m>\theta</m>. Using trigonometry, this point is <m>(\cos(\theta), \sin(\theta))</m>. Therefore, we have that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, note that <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</m> is the vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> obtained by rotating the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, which points in the direction of <m>90^\circ</m>, by <m>\theta</m> degrees counterclockwise. The resulting vector would have terminal end at the point on the unit circle whose angle is <m>90^\circ + \theta</m>. It follows that this terminal point is <m>(\cos(90^\circ + \theta), \sin(90^\circ + \theta))</m>. Using the sum rule for sine and cosine, we see that this terminal point can be expressed as <m>(-\sin(\theta), \cos(\theta))</m>. Therefore, we have that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} -\sin(\theta) \\ \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p> 
        <p>
            Thus, we have that the matrix <m>A </m> so that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x </m> results in rotating the vector <m>\vec x</m> by <m>\theta</m> degrees counterclockwise is <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \amp -\sin(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \amp \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Let's choose "nice" values of <m>\theta</m> to test out our matrix <m>A</m>.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\theta = 0^\circ</m>, then <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(0^\circ) \amp -\sin(0^\circ) \\ \sin(0^\circ) \amp \cos(0^\circ) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x = \vec x</m> for all <m>\vec x \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>, so <m>T</m> does not change any input vector <m>\vec x</m>. This makes sense since rotating a vector by <m>0^\circ</m> doesn't change the vector.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\theta = 180^\circ</m>, then <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(180^\circ) \amp -\sin(180^\circ) \\ \sin(180^\circ) \amp \cos(180^\circ) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x = -\vec x</m> for all <m>\vec x \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>, so <m>T</m> makes each vector <m>\vec x</m> point in the opposite direction. This makes sense since rotating a vector by <m>180^\circ</m> also makes vectors point in the opposite direction.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\theta = 90^\circ</m>, then <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(90^\circ) \amp -\sin(90^\circ) \\ \sin(90^\circ) \amp \cos(90^\circ) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. To see if <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x</m> actually does rotate vectors counterclockwise by <m>90^\circ</m>, let's calculate <m>T(\vec x)</m> for some special <m>\vec x \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <m>\vec x</m> pointing in the direction of <m>0^\circ</m>: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</me> which points in the direction of <m>90^\circ</m>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <m>\vec x</m> pointing in the direction of <m>90^\circ</m>: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me> which points in the direction of <m>180^\circ</m>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <m>\vec x</m> pointing in the direction of <m>30^\circ</m>: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</me> which points in the direction of <m>120^\circ</m>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <m>\vec x</m> pointing in the direction of <m>45^\circ</m>: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</me> which points in the direction of <m>135^\circ</m>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        These four examples provide evidence supporting that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x</m> is rotating vectors counterclockwise by <m>90^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      There is a long list of geometric transformations of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> in many linear algebra texts
      (reflections, rotations, contractions and expansions, shears, projections, and more). Several are included at the end of this section.
    </p>

  </page>

  <page xml:id="onto">
    <title>Onto Linear Transformations</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-onto">
      <title>Onto</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> is <term>onto</term> if for every
          <m>\vec b\in \mathbb{R}^m</m> there exists <m>\vec x\in \mathbb{R}^n</m> such that
          <m>T(\vec x)=\vec b</m>. In otherwords, a linear transformation is onto if the <em>range</em> of <m>T</m> equals the <em>codomain</em> of <m>T</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Onto is an <em>existence property</em>: for any <m>\vec b\in\mathbb{R}^m</m>, the system
      <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a solution (where <m>A</m> is the standard matrix of <m>T</m>).
    </p>

    <p><em>Examples</em></p>
    <ul>
      <li>A rotation on the plane is onto.</li>
      <li>A projection in the plane is not onto.</li>
    </ul>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-onto-equivalences" >
      <title>Onto: Equivalent Statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For a linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> with standard matrix <m>A</m>,
          the following are equivalent:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><m>T</m> is onto.</li>
          <li>The columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.</li>
          <li>The matrix <m>A</m> has a pivot in every row (equivalently, <m>m</m> pivotal columns).</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </page>

  <page xml:id="one-to-one">
    <title>One-to-One Linear Transformations</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-one-to-one" >
      <title>One-to-One</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> is <term>one-to-one</term>
          if for every <m>\vec b\in\mathbb{R}^m</m> there is at most one (possibly none)
          <m>\vec x\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> such that <m>T(\vec x)=\vec b</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      One-to-one is a <em>uniqueness</em> property; it does not assert existence for all <m>\vec b</m>.
    </p>

    <p><em>Examples</em></p>
    <ul>
      <li>A rotation on the plane is one-to-one.</li>
      <li>A projection in the plane is not one-to-one.</li>
    </ul>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-one-to-one-equivalences">
      <title>One-to-One: Equivalent Statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For a linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> with standard matrix <m>A</m>,
          the following are equivalent:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><m>T</m> is one-to-one.</li>
          <li>The unique solution to <m>T(\vec x)=\vec 0</m> is <m>\vec x=\vec 0</m>.</li>
          <li>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</li>
          <li>Every column of <m>A</m> is pivotal (equivalently, <m>A</m> has no free variables).</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </page>



  <page xml:id="p-1-9-fill-in-matrices">
    <title>Example: Complete the Matrices</title>


    <example>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Complete the matrices below by entering numbers into the missing entries so that the stated properties are satisfied. <em>If it isn't possible, state why.</em>
        </p>
      </introduction>
        <task workspace="0.1in">
            <statement>
              <m>A</m> is a <m>2\times 3</m> standard matrix for a one-to-one linear transformation.
            <me>
              A=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 0 \amp \\
                0 \amp  \amp 1
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    It is not possible to make <m>A</m> the standard matrix for a one-to-one linear transformation since doing so would require <m>A</m> to have a pivot in every column which cannot happen since the number of pivots is at most 2 (restricted by the number of rows). In fact, it is <em>never</em> possible for a <m>2 \times 3</m> matrix to represent a one-to-one linear transformation. Geometrically, this means that no linear transformation from <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> can bo one-to-one. This should make sense to be impossible since there are more input vectors (3 dimensions worth) than output vectors (2 dimensions worth) so many input vectors will correspond to the same output vector.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In this example, no matter how you fill in the blanks, you will always have a pivot in each row of <m>A</m>. Therefore, <m>A</m> will definitely represent an <em>onto</em> linear transformation.
                </p>
            </solution>
          </task>

          <task workspace="0.1in">
            <statement>
              <m>B</m> is a <m>3\times 2</m> standard matrix for an onto linear transformation.
            <me>
              B=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp \\
                 \amp \\
                 \amp 
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    It is not possible for <m>B</m> to represent an onto linear transformation since doing so would require <m>B</m> to have a pivot in every row, which is not possible since <m>B</m> can have at most 2 pivots (restricted by the number of columns). In fact, <em>no</em> <m>3 \times 2</m> matrix can ever represent an onto linear transformation since the most pivots such a matrix could have is 2, which means at least one of the rows will be missing a pivot. Geometrically, this is saying that no linear transformation from <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> can bo onto. This should make sense to be impossible since there are fewer input vectors (2 dimensions worth) than output vectors (3 dimensions worth) so how could you cover all the codomain.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In this example, there is a way to fill in the blanks to make <m>B</m> represent a one-to-one linear transformation, but also a way to fill in the blanks so that <m>B</m> represents a non one-to-one linear transformation.
                </p>
            </solution>
          </task>

          <task workspace="0.1in">
            <statement>
              <m>C</m> is a <m>3\times 3</m> standard matrix of a linear transformation that is one-to-one and onto.
            <me>
              C=
              \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
                 \amp  \amp \\
                 \amp  \amp 
              \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Note that in order for <m>C</m> to represent a one-to-one linear transformation, we need <m>C</m> to have a pivot in every column. The matrix <me>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me> has a pivot in every columns. Note that <m>C</m> also has a pivot in every row, so it also represents an onto linear transformation. In fact, every square matrix that has a pivot in every column <em>must</em> also have a pivot in every row. Therefore, for square matrices, the matrix will either represent a linaer transformation which is both one-to-one and onto OR will represent a linear transformation that is neither one-to-one nor onto.
                </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-linear-transform-3d-onto-oto" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Define a linear transformation by</p>
        <me>
          T(x_1,x_2)=(3x_1+x_2,\; 5x_1+7x_2,\; x_1+3x_2).
        </me>
        <p>
          Is <m>T</m> one-to-one? Is <m>T</m> onto?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 3x_1 + x_2 \\ 5x_1 + 7x_2 \\ x_1 + 3x_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Thus, the matrix that represent <m>T</m> is <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -8 \\ 0 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me> has a pivot in each column, but not a pivot in each row. Therefore, <m>T</m> is a linear transformation which is one-to-one, but not onto. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>


